  "notes": "Normal distribution; cost = numel(output).",
  "notes_sections": [
    "The probability density for the Gaussian distribution is",
    ".. math:: p(x) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{ 2 \\pi \\sigma^2 }} e^{ - \\frac{ (x - \\mu)^2 } {2 \\sigma^2} },",
    "where :math:`\\mu` is the mean and :math:`\\sigma` the standard deviation. The square of the standard deviation, :math:`\\sigma^2`, is called the variance.",
    "The function has its peak at the mean, and its \"spread\" increases with the standard deviation (the function reaches 0.607 times its maximum at :math:`x + \\sigma` and :math:`x - \\sigma` [2]_).  This implies that :meth:`normal` is more likely to return samples lying close to the mean, rather than those far away."
  ],
